WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.720
You know, usually when we talk about a medical diagnosis, there is this deep, almost unconscious expectation of precision.

00:08.020 --> 00:09.900
Oh, absolutely. We want it to be clean.

00:10.100 --> 00:11.960
Right. We want it to feel like engineering.

00:12.120 --> 00:15.700
So imagine you fall off a ladder, you break your arm, and you go to the hospital.

00:15.940 --> 00:20.100
You're sitting in that cold room with the plastic chairs, smelling the antiseptic.

00:20.160 --> 00:22.120
I can picture it. It's not a great place to be.

00:22.260 --> 00:23.160
No, it's awful.

00:23.340 --> 00:23.540
Yeah.

00:23.540 --> 00:30.840
But eventually, the doctor puts your x-ray up on the light board, and there is that jagged, glowing white line across the bone.

00:30.960 --> 00:31.200
Yeah.

00:31.360 --> 00:35.500
The doctor just points a pen at it and says, you know, there it is. That is the problem.

00:35.540 --> 00:38.820
And honestly, it is incredibly comforting in a strange way.

00:39.000 --> 00:41.240
It really is, because it's binary.

00:41.420 --> 00:44.900
Exactly. Broken or not broken, it is undeniably visible.

00:45.240 --> 00:52.340
The ambiguity of your pain is suddenly cleanly categorized into a physical object you can literally point to.

00:52.340 --> 01:00.420
A completely clean distinction. And I think we carry that desire for a clean binary snapshot into almost every other aspect of our lives.

01:00.460 --> 01:01.060
Oh, without a doubt.

01:01.240 --> 01:08.400
But then you step into the world of human identity. You step into the mechanics of consciousness or, you know, how we actually move through time.

01:08.520 --> 01:11.240
And suddenly that x-ray machine is completely useless.

01:11.460 --> 01:15.160
Totally useless. Yet we still crave those snapshots, don't we?

01:15.160 --> 01:23.200
I mean, we want a driver's license or a credit score or even a personality test to do the exact same thing that the medical scan does.

01:23.520 --> 01:27.460
We want to point to a piece of paper and say, ah, there I am. That static picture is me.

01:27.680 --> 01:32.000
Right. Which, as we're going to see today, is entirely a cognitive illusion.

01:32.280 --> 01:37.260
Because your true identity, I mean, structurally speaking, isn't that frozen snapshot at all?

01:37.260 --> 01:38.120
No, it's not.

01:38.340 --> 01:43.860
If we go back to your broken arm, the reality of that arm isn't the single frame of the x-ray.

01:44.160 --> 01:50.760
The reality is the entire messy, irreversible history of how that specific bone grew over decades.

01:50.880 --> 01:53.260
Like the childhood diet, the genetics, all of it.

01:53.340 --> 01:59.880
Exactly. The exact velocity and angle at which it fractured, the biological cascade of how it healed over months,

01:59.940 --> 02:05.480
and even every single step you chose to take or are favored slightly differently for the rest of your life because of that injury.

02:05.480 --> 02:09.840
It's a living, breathing, irreversible log of events.

02:10.060 --> 02:10.540
It is.

02:10.680 --> 02:19.240
And the overarching thesis we are exploring in this deep dive today is that the moment we try to freeze that log into a static snapshot,

02:19.700 --> 02:23.780
the moment we try to reduce a human being to an x-ray or a data point,

02:23.980 --> 02:27.160
we actually destroy the very structural integrity that makes you you.

02:27.320 --> 02:30.420
And that structural destruction isn't just a philosophical metaphor.

02:30.420 --> 02:37.700
According to the incredibly dense research we are unpacking today, it is a literal mathematical crisis.

02:37.840 --> 02:41.300
Like a crisis that is tearing apart our digital and economic systems right now.

02:41.380 --> 02:42.420
Yes, exactly.

02:42.600 --> 02:44.700
Which brings us to the mission for this deep dive.

02:45.280 --> 02:51.540
Today, we are immersing ourselves in a truly radical, mathematically rigorous paper published in March 2026.

02:51.720 --> 02:54.040
A very recent, very heavy piece of work.

02:54.160 --> 02:54.660
Very heavy.

02:54.660 --> 02:58.280
The author goes by the handle Fliction, or Fliction, depending on how you pronounce it.

02:58.360 --> 03:04.480
And the paper is titled Process, Projection, and Power Toward a Unified Ontology of Choice, Causality, and Value.

03:04.580 --> 03:05.160
Quite a mouthful.

03:05.260 --> 03:05.560
It is.

03:05.840 --> 03:11.280
And alongside that, we will be deeply exploring the core theorems of an interconnected framework known as the compiled self.

03:11.480 --> 03:15.300
I just have to say, it is a staggering amount of material to synthesize.

03:15.680 --> 03:18.780
The ambition of this author is off the charts.

03:18.860 --> 03:19.080
Right.

03:19.080 --> 03:36.340
They are attempting to build a single, cohesive, formal, mathematical architecture that connects the deepest physical mysteries of time straight up through the cognitive experience of human consciousness and all the way out into the macroeconomics of global coordination.

03:36.660 --> 03:40.120
It's basically a theory of everything, but applied to human identity.

03:40.420 --> 03:41.060
Exactly.

03:41.300 --> 03:44.860
So our goal today is to decode this architecture for you, the listener.

03:45.240 --> 03:48.060
We're going to look under the hood of reality itself.

03:48.060 --> 03:53.080
We'll explore why classical physics fails to explain what it feels like to be alive.

03:53.220 --> 03:54.400
A huge topic on its own.

03:54.520 --> 03:54.860
For sure.

03:55.140 --> 04:09.480
We'll also cover how human identity is mathematically constructed from moment to moment, and why modern algorithms, the ones currently running our society, are mathematically guaranteed to degrade that identity by flattening it into what the paper calls one-dimensional slop.

04:09.780 --> 04:12.000
We are also going to look at the geometry of how you make choices.

04:12.000 --> 04:18.160
And perhaps most importantly, we will examine the highly technical blueprint the author proposes at the end of the paper.

04:18.520 --> 04:19.520
The cure, basically.

04:19.740 --> 04:19.900
Right.

04:19.960 --> 04:25.420
A new computational grammar designed to save complex digital and economic systems from total collapse.

04:25.720 --> 04:27.520
It is a massive intellectual journey.

04:28.100 --> 04:33.960
But before we really get into the mechanics of the math and the philosophy, I want to take a moment to be completely transparent with you.

04:33.960 --> 04:35.920
Yeah, we need a quick disclaimer here.

04:36.060 --> 04:36.260
Right.

04:36.440 --> 04:42.340
Because the sources we are working from today dive fearlessly into some incredibly heavy systemic critiques.

04:43.200 --> 04:51.120
The text aggressively analyzes capitalism, the consolidation of corporate power, economic extraction, and institutional decay.

04:51.120 --> 04:55.380
It uses these economic models to literally prove its mathematical points.

04:56.020 --> 04:59.940
The systemic analysis is woven directly into the topology of the math.

05:00.320 --> 05:04.660
The author does not separate the physics of time from the realities of modern labor.

05:04.960 --> 05:05.360
Exactly.

05:05.900 --> 05:12.960
Because of that, I need to explicitly state that our mission today is to impartially report on the math and the frameworks provided in these texts.

05:13.240 --> 05:17.220
We are not endorsing any political, economic, or ideological viewpoints.

05:17.300 --> 05:19.600
We are not taking sides on the paper's systemic critiques.

05:19.900 --> 05:20.240
Right.

05:20.240 --> 05:30.660
We are simply acting as your guides, exploring the profound and honestly mind-bending concepts contained in this text to see what we can learn from the architecture it proposes.

05:31.000 --> 05:40.540
And if we are going to understand this new architecture, this math of the compiled self, we have to start by completely demolishing our default assumptions about how the universe works.

05:40.880 --> 05:43.080
We have to start at the very bottom layer of reality.

05:43.180 --> 05:43.640
We do.

05:43.780 --> 05:44.300
Let's do it.

05:44.300 --> 05:51.960
So, in classical science, basically, since the Enlightenment and Isaac Newton, we have treated reality as being fundamentally made up of static objects.

05:52.180 --> 05:52.400
Right.

05:52.560 --> 05:54.720
We look around and we think the universe is a giant container.

05:55.660 --> 05:57.380
And inside that container are things.

05:57.940 --> 06:00.620
Particles, planets, chairs, people, dollars.

06:01.080 --> 06:05.120
And then as a secondary phenomenon, those things occasionally move or change state.

06:05.440 --> 06:08.360
This is what fliction refers to as an ontology of being.

06:08.360 --> 06:08.700
Okay.

06:09.080 --> 06:10.120
Unpack that term for us.

06:10.180 --> 06:13.560
Well, ontology is just the philosophical study of what actually exists.

06:13.840 --> 06:22.220
So, an ontology of being is the core assumption that static stuff matter, objects, isolated entities, is the primary ingredient of reality.

06:22.580 --> 06:24.140
I always think of it like a game of pool.

06:24.760 --> 06:33.460
In classical science, we treat the universe like a set of billiard balls sitting motionless on a green felt table, just waiting for the cue ball to strike them.

06:33.680 --> 06:34.480
That's a great visual.

06:34.480 --> 06:38.360
The being, the static ball, is the default state of the universe.

06:39.000 --> 06:44.900
The doing the movement across the table is just an accidental property that happens to the being when force is applied.

06:45.140 --> 06:48.400
That is the perfect way to visualize the classical mindset.

06:48.980 --> 06:51.960
But Fliction's paper completely inverts that paradigm.

06:52.740 --> 06:56.640
It argues that classical science is looking at reality entirely backward.

06:56.940 --> 06:57.420
Backward how?

06:57.620 --> 07:01.160
The paper proposes what it calls an ontology of becoming.

07:01.160 --> 07:11.020
In this framework, transitions, choices, processes, the irreversible changes from one state to another, those are not accidents happening to static objects.

07:11.380 --> 07:14.880
The transitions are the actual fundamental building blocks of reality.

07:15.140 --> 07:15.480
Okay, wait.

07:15.560 --> 07:16.800
So, the doing is the default?

07:17.040 --> 07:19.560
The doing is the only fundamental reality.

07:19.880 --> 07:23.160
Everything we think of as a static object is actually just a secondary projection.

07:23.880 --> 07:24.440
Like a shadow.

07:24.440 --> 07:25.120
Exactly.

07:25.560 --> 07:29.420
It's a temporary shadow cast by an underlying continuous process.

07:30.020 --> 07:32.220
To use your analogy, there are no billiard balls.

07:32.480 --> 07:32.900
Wait, really?

07:33.120 --> 07:33.360
None?

07:33.600 --> 07:33.980
None.

07:34.320 --> 07:37.300
There is only the continuous process of momentum and collision.

07:37.780 --> 07:45.400
And when that process loops tightly enough in a localized area, it creates the temporary localized illusion of a solid sphere.

07:45.560 --> 07:46.020
Oh, wow.

07:46.020 --> 07:51.340
You, as a human being, are not a static object that occasionally makes a choice.

07:51.640 --> 07:57.140
You are the continuous process of making choices which generates the temporary interface of a person.

07:57.380 --> 07:59.280
That is a total ontological flip.

07:59.380 --> 08:03.620
It takes a second for the brain to even process that because our language is so noun heavy.

08:03.840 --> 08:04.480
Oh, definitely.

08:04.760 --> 08:05.800
We're wired for nouns.

08:06.020 --> 08:08.740
We want to be nouns, but the paper says we are verbs.

08:08.740 --> 08:15.620
And to see why this radical flip is mathematically necessary, we have to look at one of the biggest failures in modern science.

08:16.300 --> 08:19.640
We have to talk about David Chalmers and the hard problem of consciousness.

08:19.860 --> 08:23.840
Because this is exactly where the billiard ball model of the universe completely breaks down.

08:24.080 --> 08:24.740
It really is.

08:25.080 --> 08:27.920
It's the ultimate roadblock for the ontology of being.

08:28.840 --> 08:36.760
For anyone who hasn't encountered this concept, the philosopher David Chalmers formulated the hard problem of consciousness in the 1990s.

08:36.760 --> 08:39.720
And it asks a deceptively simple question.

08:40.520 --> 08:43.400
How does physical matter create subjective experience?

08:43.660 --> 08:43.780
Right.

08:44.140 --> 08:49.320
Because if the universe is just static things bumping into each other, where does the feeling come from?

08:49.840 --> 08:53.080
We can map the neural pathways of the human brain perfectly.

08:53.380 --> 08:54.560
We can look at the x-ray.

08:54.780 --> 08:57.540
We can see the electrical signals jumping across the synapses.

08:57.840 --> 09:00.420
We can map the exact chemistry of serotonin and dopamine.

09:00.680 --> 09:01.140
Exactly.

09:01.140 --> 09:10.460
But none of that physical, mechanical interaction tells us why it feels like something to see the color red or to taste a strawberry or to feel grief.

09:10.540 --> 09:10.940
Exactly.

09:11.200 --> 09:16.180
The physics gives us the blind mechanics, but it completely fails to account for the first-person perspective.

09:16.760 --> 09:19.880
The rich, qualitative, internal experience of being alive.

09:20.040 --> 09:20.260
Right.

09:20.580 --> 09:25.860
Physics can explain how the eye processes a wavelength of light, which is what Chalmers calls the easy problem.

09:26.000 --> 09:28.220
Which isn't actually easy, but comparatively.

09:28.540 --> 09:28.800
Right.

09:28.800 --> 09:32.520
But it cannot explain the experience of redness.

09:33.040 --> 09:34.280
That is the hard problem.

09:34.680 --> 09:39.340
And the text brings in the work of a systems theorist named Forrest Landry here, which I found fascinating.

09:40.420 --> 09:47.060
Landry argues that the reason traditional physics can't solve the hard problem is because of the foundational perspective from which physics is built.

09:47.180 --> 09:47.480
Yes.

09:48.000 --> 09:54.520
Landry points out that when we build physical models of the universe, whether it's Newtonian mechanics or Einstein's relativity,

09:54.780 --> 09:58.340
we construct them exclusively from a third-person perspective.

09:58.340 --> 09:59.460
We step outside of it.

09:59.560 --> 10:02.060
We step outside the universe to look at it as a whole.

10:02.280 --> 10:06.040
And when we do that, we create what physicists call the block universe.

10:06.380 --> 10:07.120
The block universe.

10:07.480 --> 10:07.720
Yeah.

10:07.960 --> 10:15.920
This is the idea that time isn't actually flowing, but that time is just another geometric dimension, exactly like length, width, or height.

10:15.920 --> 10:16.560
Precisely.

10:16.560 --> 10:29.560
In the mathematics of general relativity, every single moment in time, the Big Bang, the moment you were born, the present second, and the eventual heat death of the universe, it all exists simultaneously as a static four-dimensional block.

10:29.640 --> 10:30.720
It's all just there.

10:31.080 --> 10:31.980
It's all just there.

10:31.980 --> 10:35.240
In those physical equations, time is perfectly symmetric.

10:35.880 --> 10:40.160
You can run the math forward or you can run the math backward, and the equations work exactly the same.

10:40.560 --> 10:43.700
There is no mathematical distinction between the past and the future.

10:43.700 --> 10:49.840
I always try to visualize the block universe like a digital movie file sitting on my computer's hard drive.

10:49.900 --> 10:50.140
Okay.

10:50.260 --> 10:50.780
I like that.

10:50.920 --> 10:57.520
The entire movie, from the opening credits to the end scene, exists simultaneously on the disk.

10:57.980 --> 11:03.860
The physics equations give us the progress bar at the bottom of the screen, and that progress bar is perfectly symmetric.

11:03.860 --> 11:10.720
As an observer outside the movie, I can drag my mounts and click to minute two, or I can click to minute 90.

11:11.020 --> 11:12.740
It's all equally accessible data.

11:12.780 --> 11:12.960
Right.

11:13.060 --> 11:16.280
That is the third-person block universe view of reality.

11:16.400 --> 11:24.380
It is a brilliant mathematical model for calculating planetary orbits, but it has a fatal flaw when it comes to human reality.

11:24.540 --> 11:28.040
Because that is absolutely not how you and I actually experience reality.

11:28.100 --> 11:28.420
It isn't.

11:28.460 --> 11:29.040
Not even close.

11:29.040 --> 11:34.640
No, we don't experience our lives as a symmetric progress bar where we can jump back to yesterday.

11:35.020 --> 11:38.840
We experience time as a relentless, moving laser.

11:39.480 --> 11:44.480
We are the playhead on the progress bar, reading exactly one frame of reality at a time.

11:44.520 --> 11:45.400
That's a great way to put it.

11:45.520 --> 11:46.120
The playhead.

11:46.440 --> 11:48.580
The first-person perspective is the playhead.

11:49.180 --> 11:55.280
As it moves, it leaves a trail of watched frames behind it, the fixed, irreversible past.

11:55.280 --> 12:00.440
And it looks forward into an unplayed buffer, the open, undetermined future.

12:01.300 --> 12:07.680
The block universe progress bar might be symmetric, but the playhead's journey is aggressively, violently asymmetric.

12:07.800 --> 12:08.940
It only goes in one direction.

12:09.100 --> 12:15.260
And classical science, because it only believes in the third-person block universe, has no explanation for the playhead.

12:15.400 --> 12:16.260
They just ignore it.

12:16.260 --> 12:24.440
In fact, many strict materialist physicists will argue that the feeling of, you know, the sensation of time passing is literally just a psychological illusion.

12:24.840 --> 12:32.120
They argue that the static progress bar is the objective reality, and your subjective feeling of the playhead moving is just a trick your brain is playing on you.

12:32.280 --> 12:35.780
Which feels incredibly insulting to my daily experience, frankly.

12:35.920 --> 12:36.520
Oh, absolutely.

12:36.520 --> 12:41.060
But here is where Flickshinian's paper introduces its radical solution to the hard problem.

12:41.800 --> 12:44.660
The paper says, no, the physicists have it backwards.

12:45.800 --> 12:49.880
The static block universe, the progress bar, is the mathematical abstraction.

12:50.540 --> 12:53.440
The moving playhead is the fundamental reality of the universe.

12:53.880 --> 12:56.180
This is the core of the ontology of becoming.

12:56.560 --> 13:01.360
The paper argues that consciousness isn't some magical, ethereal substance floating in your head.

13:01.360 --> 13:06.500
It isn't some emergent smoke that gets magically generated when brain cells get complex enough.

13:07.340 --> 13:11.700
Consciousness is the fundamental internal experience of temporal asymmetry.

13:11.840 --> 13:13.440
Let's slow down and really unpack that.

13:13.800 --> 13:16.580
Consciousness is the internal experience of temporal asymmetry.

13:17.120 --> 13:18.280
So going back to the playhead.

13:19.340 --> 13:22.200
Consciousness is just the friction of that playhead moving forward.

13:22.640 --> 13:23.440
In a sense, yes.

13:23.640 --> 13:25.900
Think about what is actually happening at the present moment.

13:25.980 --> 13:27.400
You are standing at the edge of the present.

13:27.400 --> 13:31.500
In front of you is a space of multiple, undetermined, possible futures.

13:31.820 --> 13:33.120
You have to make a choice.

13:33.420 --> 13:39.480
The moment you make a choice, you collapse all those myriad possibilities into a single, fixed, irreversible historical fact.

13:39.720 --> 13:43.040
You take the fluid future and you forge it into the solid past.

13:43.340 --> 13:48.440
And that transition from possibility to fixed history is mathematically asymmetric.

13:48.560 --> 13:49.460
You can't undo it.

13:49.520 --> 13:49.960
Exactly.

13:49.960 --> 13:59.080
And what Fliction argues is that this physical collapse, this transition from many futures to one past, has an internal subjective aspect to it.

13:59.180 --> 14:01.040
That internal aspect is consciousness.

14:01.440 --> 14:01.560
Wow.

14:01.900 --> 14:08.560
Subjective experience is simply what it feels like from the inside to be the process that resolves possibilities into history.

14:08.560 --> 14:13.780
We are not static biological objects that somehow possess consciousness as a property.

14:14.020 --> 14:17.320
We are the active, irreversible process of time flowing.

14:17.520 --> 14:20.420
And the feeling of being alive is the sensation of that flow.

14:20.600 --> 14:20.820
Okay.

14:20.920 --> 14:22.780
My mind is already stretched to its limits.

14:23.540 --> 14:29.960
We have shifted from a universe made of static billiard balls to a universe made of pure process, transition, and flow.

14:30.120 --> 14:30.420
Yes.

14:30.620 --> 14:34.200
The problem of consciousness is solved by realizing we're the flow of time.

14:34.720 --> 14:38.040
But this immediately raises a huge, terrifying question for me.

14:38.040 --> 14:38.440
Which is?

14:38.640 --> 14:47.600
If reality is just this endless, continuous sequence of transitions, if there is no solid, static stuff at the bottom of it all, how do we not just dissolve into pure chaos?

14:47.760 --> 14:53.720
If I am not a physical object, but just a verb, how does a stable me exist at all?

14:54.040 --> 14:56.860
How do I wake up feeling like the same person I was yesterday?

14:57.360 --> 15:02.600
That is the exact tension that drives the entire second major section of the source material.

15:02.600 --> 15:16.320
If we throw out the comforting idea of a static soul locked in a jar, or the idea that your identity is just your physical body, especially since your biological cells are constantly dying and replacing themselves, what is human identity?

15:16.480 --> 15:16.600
Right.

15:16.680 --> 15:17.680
What is holding it together?

15:17.900 --> 15:18.240
Exactly.

15:18.700 --> 15:23.100
The paper introduces a formal, mathematically rigorous architecture to answer this.

15:23.360 --> 15:25.240
It is called the compiled self.

15:25.440 --> 15:26.340
The compiled self.

15:26.340 --> 15:27.900
I love the terminology here.

15:28.380 --> 15:32.240
It implies that identity isn't a pre-existing thing you were handed at birth.

15:32.720 --> 15:35.860
It is an ongoing, dynamically maintained abstraction.

15:36.340 --> 15:38.260
It is something you have to continuously compute.

15:38.480 --> 15:39.120
It is an achievement.

15:39.120 --> 15:48.820
Yes, and to prove why we need this incredibly specific mathematical architecture to maintain an identity, the paper actually starts by showing us what happens when an identity fails to compile.

15:49.200 --> 15:52.680
It shows us a massive structural failure in artificial intelligence.

15:52.940 --> 15:55.460
Yes, the Markov name generator experiment.

15:56.020 --> 16:00.760
The author uses this experiment as a beautiful, isolating proof of concept.

16:01.360 --> 16:02.640
Let's break down exactly what happened.

16:02.720 --> 16:03.120
Please do.

16:03.120 --> 16:07.840
The author built a relatively simple AI system based on a Markov chain.

16:08.420 --> 16:10.700
A Markov chain is essentially a probability engine.

16:11.300 --> 16:16.360
It looks at a current state and predicts the most likely next state based on historical training data.

16:16.920 --> 16:21.140
So in this case, the author trained it on English phonetic rules and historical names.

16:21.260 --> 16:21.520
Correct.

16:21.900 --> 16:26.660
The goal was to generate completely novel, unique names that had never existed before.

16:26.660 --> 16:34.680
The system would look at a letter, say T, and use probability to guess that H or R should come next and then guess the next vowel and so on.

16:34.900 --> 16:35.320
Okay, makes sense.

16:35.440 --> 16:39.100
And on a purely lexical level, the experiment was a massive success.

16:39.300 --> 16:39.560
Oh, yeah.

16:39.660 --> 16:41.380
The names it spit out were fantastic.

16:41.840 --> 16:43.220
They sounded lexically plausible.

16:43.780 --> 16:48.560
They sounded like they could belong to real historical figures or characters in a high fantasy novel.

16:48.760 --> 16:51.480
Names like Fowler or Caelan or Vespera.

16:51.780 --> 16:53.100
They had a beautiful phonetic surface.

16:53.100 --> 16:57.260
But then the author took the experiment to the crucial second stage.

16:57.800 --> 17:07.620
They took these brand new phonetically unique names and fed them into a massive state-of-the-art large language model, a neural network with billions of parameters.

17:07.960 --> 17:09.600
Like the AIs everyone is using today.

17:09.700 --> 17:10.240
Exactly.

17:10.720 --> 17:12.540
And the author prompted the language model.

17:13.040 --> 17:13.640
Here is a name.

17:14.460 --> 17:19.420
Invent a backstory, a mythology, and a distinct personality for this individual.

17:19.420 --> 17:23.780
And the result was an absolute structural collapse.

17:24.060 --> 17:25.020
Complete semantic failure.

17:25.240 --> 17:37.140
No matter how phonetically unique the names were, no matter how different Fowler sounded from Caelan, the language model immediately collapsed their backstories into the exact same handful of generic, repetitive tropes.

17:37.200 --> 17:38.040
Every single time.

17:38.040 --> 17:43.420
Every single name became an ancient, wise, sage living in the woods or a cyclical deity of nature and balance.

17:43.880 --> 17:46.400
The AI created lexical novelty on the surface.

17:46.900 --> 17:50.040
But when asked to generate an identity, it fell into a generic sinkhole.

17:50.900 --> 17:55.440
And the paper meticulously argues that this was not just a temporary glitch or a lack of training data.

17:55.600 --> 17:57.040
It was a mathematical inevitability.

17:57.860 --> 17:58.520
Why did it happen?

17:58.860 --> 18:02.100
Because the generated names lacked what Fliction calls history coupling.

18:02.400 --> 18:03.120
History coupling.

18:03.300 --> 18:04.180
Let's dig into that.

18:04.180 --> 18:10.060
When the Markov chain generated the word Thaler, each letter was chosen probabilistically in isolation.

18:10.960 --> 18:13.560
The A was chosen because it fit well after the Aish.

18:14.060 --> 18:18.420
But there was no deeper, continuous logic tying the entire name to a lived history.

18:18.900 --> 18:19.680
It was just math.

18:19.860 --> 18:20.700
Just surface math.

18:20.960 --> 18:23.840
The name had no physical or temporal constraints.

18:24.440 --> 18:26.080
It was a surface without a substrate.

18:26.400 --> 18:29.640
It's like generating a shadow without a physical object to cast the shadow.

18:29.840 --> 18:30.360
Exactly.

18:30.360 --> 18:35.420
So when the massive language model looks at that shadow and tries to interpret the person

18:35.420 --> 18:38.060
behind it, it finds nothing to grab onto.

18:38.380 --> 18:39.840
There is no historical friction.

18:40.060 --> 18:41.700
There are no underlying constraints.

18:42.280 --> 18:42.980
And without that...

18:42.980 --> 18:47.220
Without constraints to guide it, the massive probabilistic weight of the language model

18:47.220 --> 18:50.160
just defaults to the densest center of its training data.

18:50.620 --> 18:54.500
It defaults to the most generic, highly repeated archetypes of human myth.

18:54.900 --> 18:58.900
It hallucinates a generic average because the input has no sovereign uniqueness.

18:58.900 --> 19:05.760
So, if unconstrained generation isn't enough to create a distinct identity, if just making

19:05.760 --> 19:13.200
up a random string of letters or actions doesn't make us self-quitting, what is the actual mathematical

19:13.200 --> 19:16.220
requirement for an identity to exist and survive?

19:16.540 --> 19:18.560
This is where we get to the core of the paper.

19:19.100 --> 19:24.160
Fliction outlines the architecture of identity through four rigorous mathematical theorems.

19:24.160 --> 19:30.300
If you want to exist as a stable, compiled self, you must continuously satisfy these four

19:30.300 --> 19:30.860
conditions.

19:31.060 --> 19:31.900
Okay, let's go through them.

19:31.960 --> 19:33.520
The first one is the abstraction theorem.

19:33.660 --> 19:34.980
Let's unpack the abstraction theorem.

19:35.600 --> 19:39.660
The text states that a stable interface, a stable you that can be recognized and interacted

19:39.660 --> 19:45.200
with over time, only exists if a constraint functional enforces global coherence across your

19:45.200 --> 19:45.560
history.

19:45.900 --> 19:47.020
A constraint functional.

19:47.540 --> 19:52.140
In layman's terms, your identity is mathematically defined by the rules you refuse to break.

19:52.220 --> 19:52.860
Oh, that's interesting.

19:52.860 --> 19:57.200
The accumulated history of what you have done in the past acts as a rigid constraint on what

19:57.200 --> 20:00.220
you are mathematically allowed to do next if you wish to remain you.

20:00.540 --> 20:03.280
I have to admit, when I first read this, I wanted to push back aggressively.

20:03.380 --> 20:04.140
Oh, most people do.

20:04.340 --> 20:09.220
Because culturally, we are taught that true freedom means having infinite options.

20:09.820 --> 20:15.140
We think of our identity as this limitless potential, and constraints are just societal cages

20:15.140 --> 20:16.260
trapping the real me.

20:16.260 --> 20:22.120
If my identity is just an interface, hiding a bunch of contradictory chaotic impulses underneath,

20:22.660 --> 20:25.280
aren't constraints the enemy of my true self?

20:25.420 --> 20:27.920
It's a very intuitive, very human assumption.

20:28.460 --> 20:32.060
But the mathematics of complex systems proves the exact opposite.

20:32.340 --> 20:33.440
Let's look at it structurally.

20:34.040 --> 20:36.680
Imagine you are trying to build a massive skyscraper.

20:36.680 --> 20:42.680
The constraint functional is the physics beneath the architecture, the load-bearing steel beams,

20:42.980 --> 20:47.780
the poured concrete foundation, the strict laws of tension, compression, and gravity.

20:47.900 --> 20:49.000
Right, the stuff holding it out.

20:49.140 --> 20:52.960
If you suddenly decide that constraints are a cage, and you want your building to be infinitely

20:52.960 --> 20:53.820
free, what do you do?

20:53.880 --> 20:58.760
You remove the steel beams, you just start stacking glass panels and drywall on top of each

20:58.760 --> 21:00.700
other in any arbitrary shape you want.

21:01.100 --> 21:02.800
Does the building become infinitely free?

21:02.800 --> 21:05.080
No, it instantly shatters under its own weight.

21:05.540 --> 21:08.080
It ceases to be a building at all, becomes a pile of rubble.

21:08.160 --> 21:08.540
Exactly.

21:08.740 --> 21:11.640
So the constraints are not the cage trapping the building.

21:11.920 --> 21:15.920
The constraints are the bones that allow the building to exist in the first place.

21:16.280 --> 21:17.660
The constraints are the bones.

21:17.980 --> 21:18.620
I love that.

21:19.400 --> 21:25.580
Without them, any new action I take could arbitrarily contradict my past actions, and the coherent

21:25.580 --> 21:29.520
abstraction known as my personality would fracture into noise.

21:29.620 --> 21:29.980
Yes.

21:29.980 --> 21:33.500
I would be a completely different person from millisecond to millisecond.

21:33.960 --> 21:35.780
My family wouldn't recognize me.

21:35.920 --> 21:37.220
I wouldn't recognize myself.

21:37.840 --> 21:41.660
The constraints are what allow an abstraction to cohere over the span of a lifetime.

21:41.840 --> 21:43.180
That is the abstraction theorem.

21:43.360 --> 21:44.600
You must have structural bones.

21:44.600 --> 21:48.100
Which leads us directly to the second pillar, the substrate theorem.

21:48.640 --> 21:53.020
This theorem deals with the physical or digital medium that actually carries your identity.

21:53.280 --> 21:54.820
Because the math has to run on something.

21:54.920 --> 21:55.160
Right.

21:55.160 --> 21:59.840
And the substrate theorem states that whatever medium is hosting your compiled self, it must

21:59.840 --> 22:03.720
have the physical capacity to preserve your spectral signatures.

22:04.040 --> 22:04.860
Spectral signatures.

22:05.280 --> 22:09.160
We are moving from architecture into some heavy signal processing terminology here.

22:09.340 --> 22:12.960
We are, but it's vital for understanding how uniqueness survives.

22:12.960 --> 22:16.780
The paper uses Fourier transforms to explain this concept.

22:17.000 --> 22:17.680
Okay, let's pause.

22:18.640 --> 22:20.740
Walk me through a Fourier transform.

22:21.180 --> 22:25.640
I know it's a way to analyze waves, but how does it apply to human choices?

22:25.980 --> 22:26.780
Let's break it down.

22:26.780 --> 22:32.840
In mathematics, a Fourier transform is a tool that takes a very complex, messy signal, like

22:32.840 --> 22:38.140
the sound of a symphony orchestra, and breaks it apart into its fundamental continuous sine

22:38.140 --> 22:38.420
waves.

22:38.620 --> 22:38.800
Okay.

22:38.980 --> 22:43.900
It reveals the exact frequencies and amplitudes that combine to make that complex sound.

22:43.960 --> 22:46.180
So it finds the hidden rhythm inside the noise.

22:46.260 --> 22:46.680
Exactly.

22:46.940 --> 22:49.300
Now, apply that to the continuous process of your life.

22:49.540 --> 22:51.280
Imagine tracking every choice you make.

22:51.560 --> 22:56.220
The time you wake up, how you react to a stressful email, the cadence of your speech, the specific

22:56.220 --> 23:00.740
way you arrange your kitchen, if you map the continuous process of your choices over years,

23:00.900 --> 23:04.180
it creates a highly complex, multidimensional wave.

23:04.440 --> 23:05.300
Wave of behavior.

23:05.680 --> 23:09.440
And if you run a Fourier transform on that behavioral wave, you get your spectral signature.

23:09.760 --> 23:14.700
It is the deep, fundamental, mathematical frequency of how you navigate possibility space.

23:14.840 --> 23:15.380
That's fascinating.

23:15.460 --> 23:20.460
It is the generative rhythm that makes your choices distinctly yours, separating your specific

23:20.460 --> 23:23.940
process from the generic background noise of human behavior.

23:24.080 --> 23:24.840
That is beautiful.

23:24.840 --> 23:27.580
It's not just a database list of things I've done.

23:27.880 --> 23:31.180
It's the underlying acoustic resonance of my entire existence.

23:31.520 --> 23:31.720
Yes.

23:32.300 --> 23:36.920
And the substrate theorem dictates that your medium, whether it is the biological neural

23:36.920 --> 23:42.000
networks in your human brain, or potentially some future digital substrate, must be high

23:42.000 --> 23:45.220
fidelity enough to physically preserve those delicate frequencies.

23:45.480 --> 23:46.060
And if it isn't?

23:46.380 --> 23:52.060
If the medium is too compressed or too lossy, your unique frequency gets drowned out by the noise,

23:52.060 --> 23:54.180
and your identity cannot be maintained.

23:54.180 --> 23:58.680
Okay, so we have the constrained bones, and we have a high-fidelity medium preserving our

23:58.680 --> 24:00.120
unique behavioral frequency.

24:00.340 --> 24:01.820
What is the third requirement?

24:02.220 --> 24:03.720
The third is the policy theorem.

24:04.300 --> 24:08.260
This outlines the literal mathematics of surviving your own choices over the long term.

24:08.900 --> 24:14.020
It states that a viable compiled identity must continuously balance two opposing forces,

24:14.720 --> 24:16.960
restrictive actions and expansive actions.

24:16.960 --> 24:19.180
Let's ground this in reality.

24:19.700 --> 24:21.540
What happens if I fail to balance them?

24:21.840 --> 24:23.580
Let's say I only take restrictive actions.

24:24.040 --> 24:25.460
I decide the world is too chaotic.

24:25.840 --> 24:26.960
I stay inside my house.

24:27.300 --> 24:28.040
I lock the doors.

24:28.380 --> 24:30.280
I eat the exact same meal every day.

24:30.640 --> 24:35.280
I refuse to read any new books, learn any new skills, or speak to anyone I don't already

24:35.280 --> 24:35.600
know.

24:35.600 --> 24:37.580
What happens to my compiled self?

24:38.240 --> 24:42.380
Mathematically, your volume of possibility space collapses toward zero.

24:43.200 --> 24:47.400
Because you are a process of becoming, if you stop incorporating new information, the

24:47.400 --> 24:48.600
process stagnates.

24:48.640 --> 24:49.760
So I just kind of fade out.

24:50.160 --> 24:51.040
Structurally, yes.

24:51.260 --> 24:53.660
The structural complexity of your identity degrades.

24:54.080 --> 24:58.580
You cease to be a dynamic living system, and you trend toward a dead, static object.

24:59.000 --> 25:01.180
But what if I swing wildly to the other extreme?

25:01.420 --> 25:03.060
What if I only take expansive actions?

25:03.060 --> 25:06.640
I try to be a medical doctor and a concert pianist and a deep sea welder.

25:06.960 --> 25:08.600
I move to a new continent every three days.

25:09.140 --> 25:13.060
I make deep emotional commitments to 10 different people, and then abandon them all to start a

25:13.060 --> 25:13.500
new religion.

25:13.860 --> 25:14.620
That sounds exhausting.

25:14.760 --> 25:14.880
Right.

25:14.980 --> 25:18.560
I constantly contradict my previous history in the name of total exploration.

25:18.880 --> 25:20.280
Then the system explodes.

25:20.920 --> 25:25.960
Mathematically, you accumulate so much constraint tension that the surface tension of your identity

25:25.960 --> 25:26.440
pops.

25:26.920 --> 25:29.000
Remember the bones from the abstraction theorem.

25:29.260 --> 25:29.440
Yeah.

25:29.680 --> 25:31.020
The rules I refuse to break.

25:31.020 --> 25:37.260
By taking on completely contradictory, wildly expansive trajectories, you apply physics-breaking

25:37.260 --> 25:39.380
torque to your own structural foundations.

25:39.960 --> 25:43.700
You violate your own core rules, and the identity shatters.

25:43.700 --> 25:49.760
So the policy theorem proves that true intelligence, a truly stable, compiled identity, is not

25:49.760 --> 25:51.860
about maximizing your options to infinity.

25:52.460 --> 25:57.200
It's about maintaining a viable, unbroken trajectory through possibility space.

25:57.420 --> 25:57.900
Precisely.

25:58.120 --> 26:02.820
It is the delicate art of carefully balancing exploration with deep structural commitment.

26:03.040 --> 26:06.740
You must expand enough to stay alive, but restrict enough to stay coherent.

26:06.740 --> 26:10.660
This reminds me so much of navigating a digital maze in a video game.

26:11.240 --> 26:14.160
I don't know if you play many games, but there's this whole community of speedrunners

26:14.160 --> 26:15.520
who look for glitches.

26:15.600 --> 26:15.720
Right.

26:15.800 --> 26:16.820
Trying to break the game.

26:17.180 --> 26:17.540
Exactly.

26:18.020 --> 26:20.960
They try to find an unconstrained shortcut to beat the game.

26:21.500 --> 26:26.020
They look for a corner of a room where the physics engine is weak, and they ram their

26:26.020 --> 26:30.900
character into the wall until they clip through the geometry, completely bypassing the maze

26:30.900 --> 26:31.680
to reach the end.

26:32.220 --> 26:35.040
It's sometimes called hitting the squirrel's Z vector.

26:35.480 --> 26:38.240
I am familiar with the concept of boundary breaking, yes.

26:38.240 --> 26:42.880
But the fascinating thing is, when you take that unconstrained shortcut, the game doesn't

26:42.880 --> 26:45.480
actually reward you with true, liberated freedom.

26:46.020 --> 26:48.340
What usually happens when you clip out of bounds.

26:48.500 --> 26:49.800
The physics engine panics.

26:49.900 --> 26:50.140
Yeah.

26:50.520 --> 26:54.140
The graphics turn into a distorted mess of artifacting triangles.

26:54.140 --> 26:57.580
And eventually, the game logic completely crashes.

26:58.120 --> 26:59.060
You broke the constraints.

26:59.500 --> 27:03.200
And in doing so, you destroy the universe you were trying to freely explore.

27:03.520 --> 27:06.800
That is a phenomenal visualization of violating the policy theorem.

27:07.080 --> 27:11.540
True freedom in the video game is mastering the restrictive rules of the maze, not destroying

27:11.540 --> 27:12.020
the walls.

27:12.140 --> 27:13.120
Because the walls are the game.

27:13.420 --> 27:17.840
And that brings us directly to the fourth and final pillar of the compiled self, which

27:17.840 --> 27:20.660
is the mechanism that keeps you from clipping through the walls of reality.

27:21.260 --> 27:23.400
It is called the narrative type system.

27:23.400 --> 27:24.380
Narrative types.

27:24.540 --> 27:29.380
When I read this, it immediately sounded like dependent types in advanced computer programming.

27:29.760 --> 27:32.240
It is based on the exact same mathematical logic.

27:33.140 --> 27:37.620
In standard computer programming, you have basic types like an integer or a string of text.

27:38.100 --> 27:43.260
But in a dependent type system, the validity of a piece of data depends on the value of another

27:43.260 --> 27:43.980
piece of data.

27:44.260 --> 27:45.200
Give me an example of that.

27:45.200 --> 27:50.100
For example, you might have a variable that must be an integer, but it depends on another

27:50.100 --> 27:52.800
rule saying it must be strictly greater than 5.

27:53.480 --> 27:57.080
If you try to input a 3, the system physically will not compile.

27:57.540 --> 27:58.560
It throws an error.

27:58.560 --> 28:09.060
The paper argues that human identity relies on a narrative type system to act as a localized

28:09.060 --> 28:12.380
filter that enforces your global, lifelong constraints.

28:12.900 --> 28:17.660
At every single waking moment, this internal system evaluates your entire past history.

28:17.760 --> 28:18.620
Everything I've ever done.

28:18.620 --> 28:19.180
Exactly.

28:19.560 --> 28:22.400
It looks at the massive accumulated log of who you are.

28:22.800 --> 28:27.420
And based on that data, it mathematically dictates which specific actions are admissible

28:27.420 --> 28:28.440
for you to take next.

28:28.440 --> 28:34.280
So if I have spent 20 years building a life centered around radical honesty and scientific

28:34.280 --> 28:40.220
rigor, and suddenly I am faced with a choice to run a fraudulent psychic healing scam, my

28:40.220 --> 28:45.540
narrative type system evaluates that choice against my history, sees a massive structural

28:45.540 --> 28:48.520
contradiction, and essentially throws a compiler error.

28:48.900 --> 28:51.980
It makes the choice feel psychologically repugnant or impossible.

28:52.280 --> 28:52.560
Yes.

28:52.560 --> 28:58.380
It ensures that your local moment-to-moment impulsive choices don't accidentally violate the

28:58.380 --> 29:01.180
global load-bearing bones of your entire life's trajectory.

29:01.580 --> 29:06.180
It is the bouncer at the door of your possibility space, checking your ID, which is your entire

29:06.180 --> 29:09.200
past history, before letting a new choice into your reality.

29:09.540 --> 29:15.460
So to synthesize this massive architectural blueprint, a compiled self is not a static soul.

29:16.000 --> 29:21.460
It is a stable interface built on constraint functional bones, carried by a high-fidelity medium

29:21.460 --> 29:26.340
that preserves the spectral frequency of your behavior, navigating a viable path by carefully

29:26.340 --> 29:32.600
balancing expansion and restriction, all locally enforced moment-to-moment by a narrative-dependent

29:32.600 --> 29:33.260
type system.

29:33.620 --> 29:35.740
That is the complete mathematical architecture of you.

29:35.840 --> 29:36.500
It is profound.

29:36.640 --> 29:40.840
It is so much more dynamic and frankly so much more fragile than just assuming we have a permanent

29:40.840 --> 29:41.260
essence.

29:42.040 --> 29:44.980
But this brings us to a massive pivot point in the source material.

29:45.500 --> 29:47.880
We have this beautiful, intricate architecture of identity.

29:48.320 --> 29:50.840
But where does this computation actually take place?

29:50.920 --> 29:51.040
Right.

29:51.080 --> 29:52.720
It doesn't happen in a theoretical void.

29:52.720 --> 29:53.160
Exactly.

29:53.360 --> 29:55.340
It happens in a strictly governed physical reality.

29:55.600 --> 29:57.940
It happens inside the unforgiving medium of time.

29:58.320 --> 30:03.020
And this is where affliction introduces one of the most brutal, uncompromising mathematical

30:03.020 --> 30:06.460
rules in the entire paper, the log-sovereignty theorem.

30:06.700 --> 30:07.460
Log-sovereignty.

30:07.960 --> 30:13.200
The paper explicitly states that the history of a compiled self must be structurally, physically

30:13.200 --> 30:13.980
append-only.

30:14.360 --> 30:15.000
Append-only.

30:15.620 --> 30:20.900
Think of a blockchain ledger or a 19th century accountant's physical ledger written in permanent

30:20.900 --> 30:21.300
ink.

30:21.300 --> 30:24.600
The rule of an append-only system is simple.

30:25.380 --> 30:29.580
You can write new lines of data at the bottom of the page, but you can never, ever go back

30:29.580 --> 30:33.460
up the page to erase, modify, or overwrite what has already been written.

30:33.880 --> 30:36.780
Okay, I conceptually understand an append-only ledger.

30:37.180 --> 30:41.920
But let's ground this in everyday human experience, because it feels counterintuitive to modern

30:41.920 --> 30:42.260
life.

30:42.400 --> 30:42.800
How so?

30:42.940 --> 30:47.280
If I am typing a document on my laptop, I can hit the backspace key and erase a typo.

30:47.280 --> 30:52.580
If I take an unflattering photo on my smartphone, I can just tap the trash icon and delete it.

30:53.000 --> 30:53.440
It's gone.

30:54.160 --> 30:58.760
So why does a mistake matter so much to the compiled self if we live in a world where I

30:58.760 --> 30:59.540
can just hit undo?

31:00.020 --> 31:03.980
Because the paper proves that in the actual physical reality of a compiled human life,

31:04.360 --> 31:06.320
the undo button is a complete myth.

31:06.800 --> 31:09.080
This is detailed in the temporal constraint theorem.

31:09.480 --> 31:13.560
Even if you delete the photo from your smartphone's hard drive, the structural consequences of that

31:13.560 --> 31:14.760
entire event are permanent.

31:15.200 --> 31:16.600
Let's trace the consequences of that.

31:17.120 --> 31:18.020
I take the bad photo.

31:18.260 --> 31:19.320
I look at it.

31:19.660 --> 31:21.000
I feel a flash of insecurity.

31:21.460 --> 31:22.500
I move my thumb.

31:23.100 --> 31:24.120
I hit delete.

31:24.340 --> 31:24.760
Exactly.

31:24.960 --> 31:25.880
Let's look at the cascade.

31:26.600 --> 31:28.760
The photons from the screen enter your eye.

31:29.420 --> 31:34.720
The specific neural pathways in your brain fired, physically altering the synaptic weights

31:34.720 --> 31:35.840
of your biological medium.

31:36.020 --> 31:37.820
My brain literally changed.

31:38.000 --> 31:38.280
Yes.

31:38.280 --> 31:43.760
The emotional spike of insecurity slightly altered your hormone levels, changing your

31:43.760 --> 31:47.720
disposition for the next 10 minutes, which slightly altered the tone of voice you used

31:47.720 --> 31:49.980
when speaking to your partner, which altered their day.

31:50.360 --> 31:55.320
And most importantly, you now possess the permanent memory of the act of deleting the photo to

31:55.320 --> 31:55.700
hide it.

31:56.380 --> 32:00.720
The digital file is gone, but the structural wake of the event is permanently fused into my

32:00.720 --> 32:01.140
architecture.

32:01.360 --> 32:01.620
Yes.

32:01.940 --> 32:07.380
All of those secondary, biological, and historical consequences are permanently appended to the

32:07.380 --> 32:08.120
bottom of your log.

32:08.440 --> 32:10.520
You cannot backspace your neuroplasticity.

32:10.640 --> 32:10.920
Wow.

32:11.400 --> 32:15.060
The past is mathematically, structurally inaccessible for modification.

32:15.880 --> 32:20.000
This is what the paper means when it declares that time equals the asymmetry of accessibility.

32:20.500 --> 32:22.740
Time equals the asymmetry of accessibility.

32:23.420 --> 32:24.640
That is a heavy sentence.

32:24.980 --> 32:26.500
But a mathematically precise one.

32:26.960 --> 32:31.520
From your first-person perspective, standing at the playhead we discussed earlier, the future

32:31.520 --> 32:34.980
is structurally inaccessible because it isn't written in the log yet.

32:34.980 --> 32:40.440
And the past is structurally inaccessible for modification because it is already mathematically

32:40.440 --> 32:43.060
compiled into the foundation of your present moment.

32:43.300 --> 32:44.240
So I'm stuck with it.

32:44.360 --> 32:47.060
You are permanently bound to the trajectory of your choices.

32:47.500 --> 32:48.820
Every choice is load-bearing.

32:49.200 --> 32:52.820
This append-only physics of time is a complete game-changer.

32:53.380 --> 32:55.560
And the author doesn't just state this in a vacuum.

32:56.300 --> 33:01.220
The paper actually takes the time to systematically dismantle some of the most popular scientific theories

33:01.220 --> 33:07.640
of mind in cognitive science today using this exact concept of the append-only log to show

33:07.640 --> 33:08.820
why those theories fail.

33:08.980 --> 33:11.800
It is a devastating critique of the current academic consensus.

33:12.040 --> 33:12.240
Yes.

33:12.620 --> 33:17.220
The author uses the compiled self-framework to show why competing theories are structurally

33:17.220 --> 33:17.740
incomplete.

33:18.400 --> 33:20.300
Let's look at functionalism, for example.

33:20.680 --> 33:21.200
Let's do it.

33:21.780 --> 33:26.360
Functionalism is massive, especially in artificial intelligence and Silicon Valley circles.

33:26.360 --> 33:32.900
The basic premise is that mental states, consciousness, identity are just determined by their functional

33:32.900 --> 33:33.280
role.

33:33.900 --> 33:36.880
